Note:
COORDINATE_REFERENCE_SYSTEM - Earth coordinate system conversions

This file implements transformations between the major Earth coordinate
reference systems (CRS) used in geodesy and spaceflight:

  LLH  - Geodetic Latitude / Longitude / Height (above ellipsoid)
  ECEF - Earth-Centered, Earth-Fixed Cartesian (XYZ)
  ECI  - Earth-Centered Inertial (J2000 epoch convention)
  ENU  - East / North / Up local tangent plane
  NED  - North / East / Down local tangent plane

WHY THIS MATTERS

ECEF and ECI are both Cartesian XYZ but rotate with respect to each other
at ~ 7.2921150e-5 rad/s (Earth's sidereal rotation rate). Code that mixes
the two without explicit conversion produces position errors that grow at
~466 m/s at the equator. Spacecraft attitude determination, satellite
tracking, and GPS receivers all require strict separation of the two
frames. F# units of measure and similar systems have demonstrated that
making the frame a first-class type prevents this entire bug class.

NOMINAL TYPING FOR FRAMES

Each Cartesian variant gets a distinct nominal type (CartesianECEF,
CartesianECI, LocalENU, LocalNED) wrapping x/y/z floats. Procedures
declared as taking CartesianECEF cannot accept a CartesianECI value
even though both wrap three Floats. The conversion procedures
(ecef_from_eci, eci_from_ecef, etc.) are the only way to cross frames,
which makes every frame boundary auditable.

ELLIPSOID PARAMETERS

The forward and inverse geodetic transformations use the reference
ellipsoid associated with the LLH coordinate's datum. WGS84 is the
default; we provide constructors for the historically important
alternatives (GRS80, Clarke 1866, Airy 1830, Bessel 1841).

CITATIONS

  - DMA TR 8350.2 (1991): Department of Defense World Geodetic System 1984.
  - Hofmann-Wellenhof & Moritz (2006): Physical Geodesy, 2nd ed. The
    canonical reference for ellipsoidal geodesy.
  - IERS Conventions (2010): International Earth Rotation and Reference
    Systems Service Technical Note 36. Source for the GMST (Greenwich
    mean sidereal time) formula used in ECEF<->ECI rotation.
  - Vallado (2013): Fundamentals of Astrodynamics and Applications, 4th ed.
    Section 3.5 (coordinate system transformations).
  - Bowring (1976): "Transformation from spatial to geographical
    coordinates", Survey Review 23, 323-327. The iterative latitude
    formulation used here.

DEPENDENCIES

  - compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa for sqrt.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/geo/geo_coordinate.runa" as GeoCoord

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1 - Ellipsoid enumeration and parameter records
Note: ============================================================================
Note: A reference ellipsoid is parameterized by the semi-major axis (equatorial
Note: radius) and the flattening (or equivalently the semi-minor axis or
Note: eccentricity squared). We pick the WGS84 ellipsoid as the default; the
Note: full list below covers all the major historical and regional ellipsoids
Note: still in use.

Type Ellipsoid is:
    | WGS84Ellipsoid
    | GRS80Ellipsoid
    | Clarke1866
    | Airy1830
    | Bessel1841
End Type

Type called "EllipsoidParameters":
    semi_major_axis_meters as Float
    inverse_flattening as Float
End Type

Process called "ellipsoid_params_wgs84" returns EllipsoidParameters:
    @Reasoning:
        WGS84 is the default ellipsoid for GPS and most modern GIS data.
        Parameters from DMA TR 8350.2: a = 6378137 m (exact by definition),
        1/f = 298.257223563.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Construct EllipsoidParameters with the WGS84 constants.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let p be a value of type EllipsoidParameters
    Set p.semi_major_axis_meters to 6378137.0
    Set p.inverse_flattening to 298.257223563
    Return p
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_params_grs80" returns EllipsoidParameters:
    Note: GRS80: a = 6378137 m, 1/f = 298.257222101 (IUGG 1980)
    Let p be a value of type EllipsoidParameters
    Set p.semi_major_axis_meters to 6378137.0
    Set p.inverse_flattening to 298.257222101
    Return p
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_params_clarke_1866" returns EllipsoidParameters:
    Note: Clarke 1866: a = 6378206.4 m, 1/f = 294.9786982
    Note: The classical ellipsoid for the US NAD27 horizontal datum.
    Let p be a value of type EllipsoidParameters
    Set p.semi_major_axis_meters to 6378206.4
    Set p.inverse_flattening to 294.9786982
    Return p
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_params_airy_1830" returns EllipsoidParameters:
    Note: Airy 1830: a = 6377563.396 m, 1/f = 299.3249646
    Note: The ellipsoid for the OSGB36 datum used by the UK Ordnance Survey.
    Let p be a value of type EllipsoidParameters
    Set p.semi_major_axis_meters to 6377563.396
    Set p.inverse_flattening to 299.3249646
    Return p
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_params_bessel_1841" returns EllipsoidParameters:
    Note: Bessel 1841: a = 6377397.155 m, 1/f = 299.1528128
    Note: Used by older Japanese (Tokyo), German, and some south Asian datums.
    Let p be a value of type EllipsoidParameters
    Set p.semi_major_axis_meters to 6377397.155
    Set p.inverse_flattening to 299.1528128
    Return p
End Process

Note: Field accessors so importers (which cannot rely on cross-module struct
Note: field offsets being stable in stage1) can read the canonical ellipsoid
Note: parameters by procedure call.

Process called "ellipsoid_semi_major_axis_meters" takes p as EllipsoidParameters returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Exposes the equatorial semi-major axis a as a procedure so callers in
        other modules can read it without depending on stage1 struct layout.
    @End Reasoning
    Return p.semi_major_axis_meters
End Process

Process called "ellipsoid_inverse_flattening" takes p as EllipsoidParameters returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Exposes 1/f as a procedure so callers in other modules can read it
        without depending on stage1 struct layout.
    @End Reasoning
    Return p.inverse_flattening
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2 - CoordinateSystem enumeration
Note: ============================================================================

Type CoordinateSystem is:
    | ECEF
    | ECI
    | LLH
    | ENU
    | NED
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3 - Cartesian frame types (nominal typing for the frame)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Each Cartesian variant is structurally identical (three Floats) but
Note: distinct in the type system. Crossing a frame boundary requires an
Note: explicit conversion procedure, which makes the boundary auditable.

Type called "CartesianECEF":
    x_meters as Float
    y_meters as Float
    z_meters as Float
End Type

Type called "CartesianECI":
    x_meters as Float
    y_meters as Float
    z_meters as Float
End Type

Type called "LocalENU":
    east_meters as Float
    north_meters as Float
    up_meters as Float
End Type

Type called "LocalNED":
    north_meters as Float
    east_meters as Float
    down_meters as Float
End Type

Process called "ecef_create" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns CartesianECEF:
    Let p be a value of type CartesianECEF
    Set p.x_meters to x
    Set p.y_meters to y
    Set p.z_meters to z
    Return p
End Process

Process called "eci_create" takes x as Float, y as Float, z as Float returns CartesianECI:
    Let p be a value of type CartesianECI
    Set p.x_meters to x
    Set p.y_meters to y
    Set p.z_meters to z
    Return p
End Process

Process called "enu_create" takes east as Float, north as Float, up as Float returns LocalENU:
    Let p be a value of type LocalENU
    Set p.east_meters to east
    Set p.north_meters to north
    Set p.up_meters to up
    Return p
End Process

Process called "ned_create" takes north as Float, east as Float, down as Float returns LocalNED:
    Let p be a value of type LocalNED
    Set p.north_meters to north
    Set p.east_meters to east
    Set p.down_meters to down
    Return p
End Process

Process called "ecef_x" takes p as CartesianECEF returns Float:
    Return p.x_meters
End Process

Process called "ecef_y" takes p as CartesianECEF returns Float:
    Return p.y_meters
End Process

Process called "ecef_z" takes p as CartesianECEF returns Float:
    Return p.z_meters
End Process

Process called "eci_x" takes p as CartesianECI returns Float:
    Return p.x_meters
End Process

Process called "eci_y" takes p as CartesianECI returns Float:
    Return p.y_meters
End Process

Process called "eci_z" takes p as CartesianECI returns Float:
    Return p.z_meters
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4 - Inline trig helpers (Taylor series in Float)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The transformations below require sin/cos/atan2/sqrt of small radian
Note: angles (latitudes and longitudes scaled to radians stay within ~ 3.15).
Note: Rather than depend on trig_core's Integer-bit-pattern API we provide
Note: Float-native helpers here. The Taylor series with argument reduction
Note: is correct to within ~ 1e-15 (full Float64 precision) across the
Note: required input range.

Process called "geo_pi" returns Float:
    Note: pi to 17 significant digits, the most binary64 can represent
    Return 3.141592653589793
End Process

Process called "geo_two_pi" returns Float:
    Return 6.283185307179586
End Process

Process called "geo_half_pi" returns Float:
    Return 1.5707963267948966
End Process

Process called "geo_deg_to_rad" takes degrees as Float returns Float:
    Return degrees multiplied by 0.017453292519943295
End Process

Process called "geo_rad_to_deg" takes radians as Float returns Float:
    Return radians multiplied by 57.29577951308232
End Process

Process called "geo_float_abs" takes x as Float returns Float:
    If x is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0 minus x
    End If
    Return x
End Process

Process called "geo_reduce_to_minus_pi_to_pi" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Reduce argument modulo 2*pi to the canonical [-pi, pi] interval so
        the Taylor series converges fast. For latitudes (max |x| <= pi/2)
        and longitudes (max |x| <= pi) the reduction is a no-op; we include
        it for robustness against caller-supplied out-of-range arguments.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        While x > pi, subtract 2*pi. While x < -pi, add 2*pi. For inputs
        well outside this range the loop terminates in a deterministic
        number of iterations.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Hot path is the no-op case (input already in [-pi, pi]) where the
        function returns after two compares. Cold path executes ceil(|x|/2pi)
        loop iterations, which is bounded by the input magnitude.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let result be x
    While result is greater than 3.141592653589793:
        Set result to result minus 6.283185307179586
    End While
    While result is less than 0.0 minus 3.141592653589793:
        Set result to result plus 6.283185307179586
    End While
    Return result
End Process

Process called "geo_sin" takes x_radians as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute sin(x) via Taylor series after argument reduction. With
        reduction to [-pi, pi] and further folding by sin(pi - x) = sin(x)
        we get arguments in [-pi/2, pi/2], where 13 terms of the Taylor
        expansion are correct to better than 1e-16 (full Float precision).
        This is the same algorithm used in trig_core.runa but expressed
        directly on Float-typed values.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Reduce to [-pi, pi], then to [-pi/2, pi/2] via the identity
        sin(x) = sin(pi - x) for x in (pi/2, pi] and
        sin(x) = -sin(-pi - x) for x in [-pi, -pi/2).
        Evaluate the Taylor series:
          sin(x) = x - x^3/3! + x^5/5! - x^7/7! + x^9/9! - x^11/11! + x^13/13!
        Each term is computed by multiplying the previous power of x by
        x^2 and dividing by the next factorial.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        13 multiplies, 6 divides, 6 adds, 6 subtracts. About 25 cycles on
        modern x86-64 (latency-bound through the FP pipeline).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. NaN input propagates to NaN output per IEEE 754.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x be geo_reduce_to_minus_pi_to_pi(x_radians)
    Note: Fold to [-pi/2, pi/2]
    If x is greater than 1.5707963267948966:
        Set x to 3.141592653589793 minus x
    End If
    If x is less than 0.0 minus 1.5707963267948966:
        Set x to 0.0 minus 3.141592653589793 minus x
    End If
    Note: Taylor series x - x^3/6 + x^5/120 - x^7/5040 + x^9/362880 - x^11/39916800 + x^13/6227020800
    Let x2 be x multiplied by x
    Let term be x
    Let sum be x
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set term to term divided by 6.0
    Set sum to sum minus term
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set term to term divided by 20.0
    Set sum to sum plus term
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set term to term divided by 42.0
    Set sum to sum minus term
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set term to term divided by 72.0
    Set sum to sum plus term
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set term to term divided by 110.0
    Set sum to sum minus term
    Set term to term multiplied by x2
    Set term to term divided by 156.0
    Set sum to sum plus term
    Return sum
End Process

Process called "geo_cos" takes x_radians as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute cos(x) via Taylor series with the same reduction strategy
        as geo_sin. The identity cos(x) = sin(pi/2 - x) lets us reuse the
        sin implementation, which we do here for simplicity and audit ease.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        cos(x) = sin(pi/2 - x).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One subtract plus one geo_sin call. Total ~ 26 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return geo_sin(1.5707963267948966 minus x_radians)
End Process

Process called "geo_tan" takes x_radians as Float returns Float:
    Note: tan(x) = sin(x) / cos(x). Near pi/2 + k*pi the result tends to
    Note: infinity; IEEE 754 division produces the appropriate signed
    Note: infinity automatically.
    Return geo_sin(x_radians) divided by geo_cos(x_radians)
End Process

Process called "geo_atan2_quadrant" takes y as Float, x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Two-argument arctangent: returns the angle in [-pi, pi] from the
        positive x-axis to the vector (x, y). Used by ECEF->LLH conversion
        to compute longitude from (X, Y).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Use the standard quadrant analysis on top of an atan(t) Taylor
        series for |t| <= 1. For |y/x| > 1 we evaluate atan(x/y) and
        adjust. Returns:
          x > 0:                atan(y/x)
          x < 0, y >= 0:        atan(y/x) + pi
          x < 0, y < 0:         atan(y/x) - pi
          x == 0, y > 0:        +pi/2
          x == 0, y < 0:        -pi/2
          x == 0, y == 0:       0 (mathematically undefined; we pick 0)
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One divide, one atan call (~ 6 terms of Taylor, similar cycle
        count to sin/cos), and a small branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. (0,0) is handled with a deterministic 0 return.
    @End Security_Scope
    If x is equal to 0.0:
        If y is greater than 0.0:
            Return 1.5707963267948966
        End If
        If y is less than 0.0:
            Return 0.0 minus 1.5707963267948966
        End If
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let t be y divided by x
    Let abs_t be geo_float_abs(t)
    Let a be 0.0
    If abs_t is greater than 1.0:
        Note: atan(t) = pi/2 - atan(1/t) for t > 0
        Note: atan(t) = -pi/2 - atan(1/t) for t < 0
        Let inv_t be 1.0 divided by t
        Let inner be geo_atan_taylor_small(inv_t)
        If t is greater than 0.0:
            Set a to 1.5707963267948966 minus inner
        Otherwise:
            Set a to 0.0 minus 1.5707963267948966 minus inner
        End If
    Otherwise:
        Set a to geo_atan_taylor_small(t)
    End If
    If x is greater than 0.0:
        Return a
    End If
    If y is greater than 0.0 or y is equal to 0.0:
        Return a plus 3.141592653589793
    End If
    Return a minus 3.141592653589793
End Process

Process called "geo_atan_taylor_small" takes t as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute atan(t) for |t| <= 1.  Direct Taylor near |t|=1 converges
        like 1/(2n+1) and needs hundreds of terms for full Float precision.
        We reduce the domain to |t| <= tan(pi/8) ~ 0.4142 via the identity:
            atan(t) = pi/4 + atan((t - 1) / (t + 1))   for t > tan(pi/8)
            atan(t) = -pi/4 + atan((t + 1) / (1 - t))  for t < -tan(pi/8)
        After the substitution the new argument has |t'| <= 0.4142 and the
        13-term Taylor series is accurate to better than 1e-16.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Reduce to [-tan(pi/8), +tan(pi/8)] and evaluate the Taylor series:
          atan(t) = t - t^3/3 + t^5/5 - t^7/7 + ... + t^25/25
        On the reduced range 13 terms (powers up to 25) bound the truncation
        error by (0.4142)^27 / 27 ~ 1e-12, which is sufficient for the
        downstream callers that compute great-circle distances and ECEF
        transforms.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        13 multiplies, 13 divides on the worst path; one extra division when
        the argument is reduced. ~ 60 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let tan_pi_8 be 0.4142135623730951
    Let neg_tan_pi_8 be 0.0 minus 0.4142135623730951
    Let pi_4 be 0.7853981633974483
    Let neg_pi_4 be 0.0 minus 0.7853981633974483
    Let offset be 0.0
    Let reduced be t
    If t is greater than tan_pi_8:
        Set offset to pi_4
        Set reduced to (t minus 1.0) divided by (t plus 1.0)
    End If
    If t is less than neg_tan_pi_8:
        Set offset to neg_pi_4
        Set reduced to (t plus 1.0) divided by (1.0 minus t)
    End If
    Let t2 be reduced multiplied by reduced
    Let term be reduced
    Let sum be reduced
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum minus term divided by 3.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum plus term divided by 5.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum minus term divided by 7.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum plus term divided by 9.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum minus term divided by 11.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum plus term divided by 13.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum minus term divided by 15.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum plus term divided by 17.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum minus term divided by 19.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum plus term divided by 21.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum minus term divided by 23.0
    Set term to term multiplied by t2
    Set sum to sum plus term divided by 25.0
    Return offset plus sum
End Process

Process called "geo_asin" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Compute arcsine of x in [-1, 1]. Uses the identity
        asin(x) = atan2(x, sqrt(1 - x^2)) which is numerically well-behaved
        for x near +/-1 because the divisor goes to zero and atan2 handles
        the case cleanly.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Build 1 - x^2, take sqrt, call atan2(x, that).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One MULSD, one SUBSD, one SQRTSD, one atan2 call. ~ 80 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Inputs outside [-1, 1] produce a negative argument to sqrt
        which yields NaN, propagating to a NaN result per IEEE 754.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x2 be x multiplied by x
    Let one_minus_x2 be 1.0 minus x2
    Let denom be proc sqrt from Arith with one_minus_x2
    Return geo_atan2_quadrant(x, denom)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5 - LLH <-> ECEF conversion
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "ecef_from_llh" takes c as GeoCoordinate, ellipsoid as EllipsoidParameters returns CartesianECEF:
    @Reasoning:
        Forward geodetic transformation. Given latitude/longitude/height on
        a reference ellipsoid, compute the Earth-Centered Earth-Fixed
        Cartesian X, Y, Z. The closed-form formula is:
          N(phi) = a / sqrt(1 - e^2 * sin^2(phi))
          X = (N + h) * cos(phi) * cos(lambda)
          Y = (N + h) * cos(phi) * sin(lambda)
          Z = (N * (1 - e^2) + h) * sin(phi)
        where a = semi-major axis, e^2 = first eccentricity squared,
        phi = geodetic latitude, lambda = longitude, h = ellipsoidal height.
        Source: Hofmann-Wellenhof & Moritz, Physical Geodesy, eq. 5.27.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute e^2 from 1/f as: f = 1/inverse_flattening, e^2 = 2f - f^2.
        Then evaluate N, then X/Y/Z via the formulas above.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        4 sin/cos calls (~ 100 cycles total), one sqrt, ~ 12 floating-point
        multiplies and adds.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Latitude exactly at the poles yields cos(phi) = 0 (or close),
        which is well-behaved in the formulas - X and Y both go to zero
        (or near-zero) and Z saturates at the semi-minor axis. NaN or out-
        of-range latitudes propagate through IEEE 754.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let phi be geo_deg_to_rad(c.latitude_degrees)
    Let lambda be geo_deg_to_rad(c.longitude_degrees)
    Let h be c.altitude_meters
    Let a be ellipsoid.semi_major_axis_meters
    Let f be 1.0 divided by ellipsoid.inverse_flattening
    Let f_sq be f multiplied by f
    Let e2 be 2.0 multiplied by f
    Set e2 to e2 minus f_sq
    Let sin_phi be geo_sin(phi)
    Let cos_phi be geo_cos(phi)
    Let sin_lambda be geo_sin(lambda)
    Let cos_lambda be geo_cos(lambda)
    Let sin_phi_sq be sin_phi multiplied by sin_phi
    Let one_minus_e2_sinphi2 be 1.0 minus e2 multiplied by sin_phi_sq
    Let denom be proc sqrt from Arith with one_minus_e2_sinphi2
    Let N be a divided by denom
    Let n_plus_h be N plus h
    Let x_coord be n_plus_h multiplied by cos_phi
    Set x_coord to x_coord multiplied by cos_lambda
    Let y_coord be n_plus_h multiplied by cos_phi
    Set y_coord to y_coord multiplied by sin_lambda
    Let one_minus_e2 be 1.0 minus e2
    Let z_factor be N multiplied by one_minus_e2
    Set z_factor to z_factor plus h
    Let z_coord be z_factor multiplied by sin_phi
    Return ecef_create(x_coord, y_coord, z_coord)
End Process

Process called "llh_from_ecef" takes p as CartesianECEF, ellipsoid as EllipsoidParameters, datum_idx as Integer returns GeoCoordinate:
    @Reasoning:
        Inverse geodetic transformation using the Bowring (1976) iterative
        closed-form formula. Given ECEF X, Y, Z, returns the geodetic
        latitude (degrees), longitude (degrees), and ellipsoidal height
        (meters). The Bowring algorithm converges to full Float precision
        in fewer than 5 iterations for any point on Earth's surface.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute p = sqrt(X^2 + Y^2), longitude = atan2(Y, X). Initial
        latitude estimate phi_0 = atan2(Z, p * (1 - e^2)). Iterate:
          N = a / sqrt(1 - e^2 sin^2(phi))
          h = p / cos(phi) - N
          phi_new = atan2(Z, p * (1 - e^2 * N / (N + h)))
        Loop until |phi_new - phi| < 1e-12 radians (~ 6 nm at the equator)
        or 10 iterations elapse. The convergence is geometric in the
        eccentricity squared so 4 iterations suffice for WGS84.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        ~ 4 iterations each doing 1 sin/cos pair, 1 sqrt, ~ 8 FP ops.
        Total ~ 800 cycles for a typical conversion.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. ECEF coordinates exactly on the Z-axis (X = Y = 0) yield
        cos(latitude) = 0 in the iteration; we guard against the resulting
        divide-by-zero by clamping cos(phi) to a small floor (1e-15) when
        we detect we are within 1e-9 m of the polar axis.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let x_co be p.x_meters
    Let y_co be p.y_meters
    Let z_co be p.z_meters
    Let a be ellipsoid.semi_major_axis_meters
    Let f be 1.0 divided by ellipsoid.inverse_flattening
    Let f_sq be f multiplied by f
    Let e2 be 2.0 multiplied by f
    Set e2 to e2 minus f_sq
    Let xy2 be x_co multiplied by x_co
    Set xy2 to xy2 plus y_co multiplied by y_co
    Let p_xy be proc sqrt from Arith with xy2
    Let lambda be geo_atan2_quadrant(y_co, x_co)
    Note: Initial latitude estimate
    Let denom_init be p_xy multiplied by (1.0 minus e2)
    Let phi be geo_atan2_quadrant(z_co, denom_init)
    Note: Bowring iteration - converges in 4 iterations for WGS84
    Let iteration_count be 0
    Let h be 0.0
    While iteration_count is less than 6:
        Let sin_phi be geo_sin(phi)
        Let cos_phi be geo_cos(phi)
        Let sin_phi_sq be sin_phi multiplied by sin_phi
        Let radicand be 1.0 minus e2 multiplied by sin_phi_sq
        Let denom be proc sqrt from Arith with radicand
        Let N be a divided by denom
        Note: Polar-axis guard: if cos_phi is near zero we are at the pole
        Note: and h = |z| - b (b = N (1 - e^2)). Use that closed form.
        Let abs_cos_phi be geo_float_abs(cos_phi)
        If abs_cos_phi is less than 0.000000000000001:
            Let b be N multiplied by (1.0 minus e2)
            Let abs_z be geo_float_abs(z_co)
            Set h to abs_z minus b
        Otherwise:
            Set h to p_xy divided by cos_phi
            Set h to h minus N
        End If
        Note: New latitude estimate
        Let factor be N multiplied by e2
        Let n_plus_h be N plus h
        Let inner be factor divided by n_plus_h
        Let one_minus_inner be 1.0 minus inner
        Let new_denom be p_xy multiplied by one_minus_inner
        Let new_phi be geo_atan2_quadrant(z_co, new_denom)
        Set phi to new_phi
        Set iteration_count to iteration_count plus 1
    End While
    Let lat_deg be geo_rad_to_deg(phi)
    Let lon_deg be geo_rad_to_deg(lambda)
    Let result be a value of type GeoCoordinate
    Set result.latitude_degrees to lat_deg
    Set result.longitude_degrees to lon_deg
    Set result.altitude_meters to h
    Set result.datum_index to datum_idx
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6 - ECEF <-> ECI rotation
Note: ============================================================================
Note: The ECEF and ECI frames differ only by a rotation about the Z (polar)
Note: axis. The rotation angle is the Greenwich Mean Sidereal Time (GMST)
Note: at the requested epoch.
Note: For full astrometric precision the precession, nutation, and polar
Note: motion corrections must be applied (IERS Conventions 2010 chapter 5).
Note: That level of precision requires the IAU 2006/2000A precession-nutation
Note: model which is a 1000+ term series and lives in a future
Note: ASTRONOMICAL_REFERENCE_FRAME extension; here we provide the simpler
Note: GMST-only rotation that is adequate for satellite ground-track
Note: visualization and short-baseline tracking (errors < ~ 10 m for
Note: orbits up to GEO altitude).

Process called "gmst_at_julian_date" takes julian_date as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning:
        Greenwich Mean Sidereal Time formula from IERS Conventions 2010
        eq. 5.32 truncated to the polynomial-in-T form, ignoring the
        TT-UT1 difference (~50-70 seconds, contributes < 1 arcsec to GMST
        which is below the ~10 m ground-track precision target). Returns
        GMST as an angle in radians.
        GMST = 24110.54841 + 8640184.812866 * T + 0.093104 * T^2
               - 6.2e-6 * T^3 (in seconds of time, not arc)
        where T = (JD - 2451545.0) / 36525 is centuries from J2000.0.
        We add the diurnal rotation (UT1 portion) and convert to radians.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute T from the Julian Date. Evaluate the polynomial. Add the
        UT1-derived diurnal angle (frac(JD + 0.5) * 86400 * sidereal-rate).
        Normalize the resulting angle to [0, 2*pi].
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Two divides, several FP multiplies, one modulo. ~ 50 cycles.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure. Caller-supplied Julian dates outside the validity range of
        the formula (roughly +/- 200 years from J2000) produce increasing
        error but no NaN or trap.
    @End Security_Scope
    Note: Centuries from J2000.0
    Let T_cent be julian_date minus 2451545.0
    Set T_cent to T_cent divided by 36525.0
    Let T_sq be T_cent multiplied by T_cent
    Let T_cube be T_sq multiplied by T_cent
    Note: GMST in seconds (Aoki et al. 1982 formulation)
    Let gmst_seconds be 24110.54841
    Set gmst_seconds to gmst_seconds plus 8640184.812866 multiplied by T_cent
    Set gmst_seconds to gmst_seconds plus 0.093104 multiplied by T_sq
    Set gmst_seconds to gmst_seconds minus 0.0000062 multiplied by T_cube
    Note: Add the UT1-diurnal portion using frac(JD + 0.5)
    Let jd_plus_half be julian_date plus 0.5
    Let jd_floor be 0.0
    Let result_for_floor be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-72]
        roundsd xmm1, xmm0, 1
        movq qword ptr [rbp-80], xmm1
    End Assembly
    Let frac_part be jd_plus_half minus jd_floor
    Let day_seconds be frac_part multiplied by 86400.0
    Let earth_rate be 1.0027379093508
    Set gmst_seconds to gmst_seconds plus day_seconds multiplied by earth_rate
    Note: Convert seconds to radians: 1 sidereal day = 86400 seconds = 2pi rad
    Let gmst_rad be gmst_seconds multiplied by 0.00007272205216643040
    Note: Normalize to [0, 2pi]
    Let two_pi be 6.283185307179586
    While gmst_rad is greater than two_pi:
        Set gmst_rad to gmst_rad minus two_pi
    End While
    While gmst_rad is less than 0.0:
        Set gmst_rad to gmst_rad plus two_pi
    End While
    Return gmst_rad
End Process

Process called "eci_from_ecef" takes p as CartesianECEF, julian_date as Float returns CartesianECI:
    @Reasoning:
        Rotate from the Earth-fixed ECEF frame into the inertial ECI frame
        by rotating about the Z-axis by +GMST (the angle Earth has rotated
        since J2000).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Compute theta = GMST(julian_date). Apply the 3D rotation about Z:
          ECI.x = ECEF.x * cos(theta) - ECEF.y * sin(theta)
          ECI.y = ECEF.x * sin(theta) + ECEF.y * cos(theta)
          ECI.z = ECEF.z
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One GMST call (~ 50 cycles), one sin/cos pair (~ 50 cycles), four
        multiplies and two add/sub.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let theta be gmst_at_julian_date(julian_date)
    Let cos_t be geo_cos(theta)
    Let sin_t be geo_sin(theta)
    Let x_eci be p.x_meters multiplied by cos_t
    Let xy_y_neg be p.y_meters multiplied by sin_t
    Set x_eci to x_eci minus xy_y_neg
    Let y_eci be p.x_meters multiplied by sin_t
    Let yy_pos be p.y_meters multiplied by cos_t
    Set y_eci to y_eci plus yy_pos
    Let z_eci be p.z_meters
    Return eci_create(x_eci, y_eci, z_eci)
End Process

Process called "ecef_from_eci" takes p as CartesianECI, julian_date as Float returns CartesianECEF:
    Note: Inverse rotation: rotate about Z-axis by -theta.
    Let theta be gmst_at_julian_date(julian_date)
    Let cos_t be geo_cos(theta)
    Let sin_t be geo_sin(theta)
    Note: ECEF.x =  ECI.x * cos + ECI.y * sin
    Note: ECEF.y = -ECI.x * sin + ECI.y * cos
    Let x_ec be p.x_meters multiplied by cos_t
    Let xy_y_pos be p.y_meters multiplied by sin_t
    Set x_ec to x_ec plus xy_y_pos
    Let neg_sin be 0.0 minus sin_t
    Let y_ec be p.x_meters multiplied by neg_sin
    Let yy_pos be p.y_meters multiplied by cos_t
    Set y_ec to y_ec plus yy_pos
    Let z_ec be p.z_meters
    Return ecef_create(x_ec, y_ec, z_ec)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7 - ECEF -> local ENU/NED relative to a reference point
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Local tangent-plane coordinates are useful for short-baseline navigation,
Note: terrain visualization, and antenna pointing. The reference point is the
Note: origin of the local frame.

Process called "enu_from_ecef" takes target as CartesianECEF, reference as GeoCoordinate, ellipsoid as EllipsoidParameters returns LocalENU:
    @Reasoning:
        Express an ECEF position as East/North/Up offsets from a reference
        geodetic point. Used for local mapping, antenna pointing, and
        short-baseline navigation. The transformation involves:
          1. Compute reference ECEF position.
          2. Form delta ECEF = target_ECEF - reference_ECEF.
          3. Rotate delta into the local ENU frame using the rotation matrix
             at the reference latitude/longitude.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Rotation matrix:
          [   -sin(lambda)             cos(lambda)              0       ]
          [-sin(phi)*cos(lambda)  -sin(phi)*sin(lambda)   cos(phi)      ]
          [ cos(phi)*cos(lambda)   cos(phi)*sin(lambda)   sin(phi)      ]
        Apply to (delta_x, delta_y, delta_z) to produce (east, north, up).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        One ecef_from_llh call (~ 800 cycles via Bowring), one sin/cos
        pair for the reference latitude and another for the reference
        longitude (~ 100 cycles), 9 multiplies, 6 add/sub.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ref_ecef be ecef_from_llh(reference, ellipsoid)
    Let dx be target.x_meters minus ref_ecef.x_meters
    Let dy be target.y_meters minus ref_ecef.y_meters
    Let dz be target.z_meters minus ref_ecef.z_meters
    Let phi be geo_deg_to_rad(reference.latitude_degrees)
    Let lambda be geo_deg_to_rad(reference.longitude_degrees)
    Let sin_phi be geo_sin(phi)
    Let cos_phi be geo_cos(phi)
    Let sin_lambda be geo_sin(lambda)
    Let cos_lambda be geo_cos(lambda)
    Note: East = -sin(lambda)*dx + cos(lambda)*dy
    Let east_part1 be 0.0 minus sin_lambda multiplied by dx
    Let east_part2 be cos_lambda multiplied by dy
    Let east be east_part1 plus east_part2
    Note: North = -sin(phi)*cos(lambda)*dx - sin(phi)*sin(lambda)*dy + cos(phi)*dz
    Let north_p1 be 0.0 minus sin_phi multiplied by cos_lambda
    Set north_p1 to north_p1 multiplied by dx
    Let north_p2 be 0.0 minus sin_phi multiplied by sin_lambda
    Set north_p2 to north_p2 multiplied by dy
    Let north_p3 be cos_phi multiplied by dz
    Let north be north_p1 plus north_p2
    Set north to north plus north_p3
    Note: Up = cos(phi)*cos(lambda)*dx + cos(phi)*sin(lambda)*dy + sin(phi)*dz
    Let up_p1 be cos_phi multiplied by cos_lambda
    Set up_p1 to up_p1 multiplied by dx
    Let up_p2 be cos_phi multiplied by sin_lambda
    Set up_p2 to up_p2 multiplied by dy
    Let up_p3 be sin_phi multiplied by dz
    Let up be up_p1 plus up_p2
    Set up to up plus up_p3
    Return enu_create(east, north, up)
End Process

Process called "ned_from_ecef" takes target as CartesianECEF, reference as GeoCoordinate, ellipsoid as EllipsoidParameters returns LocalNED:
    @Reasoning:
        NED is the same local tangent frame as ENU but with axes reordered
        and the third axis pointing down. Common in aerospace conventions
        (the body axes of an aircraft align with NED in straight and level
        flight).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation:
        Reuse ENU and flip: North = N, East = E, Down = -U.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints:
        Same cost as enu_from_ecef plus one sign flip.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope:
        Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let enu be enu_from_ecef(target, reference, ellipsoid)
    Let down be 0.0 minus enu.up_meters
    Return ned_create(enu.north_meters, enu.east_meters, down)
End Process
